Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Amro Samaha¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area in February 2019.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset before cleaning consists of 183412 bike trip with 16 feautres ('duration_sec', 'start_time', 'end_time','start_station_id','start_station_name','start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_id', 'end_station_name', 'end_station_latitude', 'end_station_longitude', 'bike_id', 'user_type','member_birth_year', 'member_gender', and 'bike_share_for_all_trip'). Trips are in February 2019. Data after cleaning contained 174952 trips with 16 features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Main interest is the duration of trip, trips frequency by time and User types (specifically Subscriber) in terms of factors affecting and patterns.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect member's age and gender would be main assets in predicting User type. Time of the trip is expected to be the most important factor in predicting duration of trip.

In [48]:
# compute the logarithm of price to make multivariate plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

df['log_duration'] = df['duration_min'].apply(log_trans)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Duration had a very large scale of values especially high values. Log scale transformation of duration deemed useful and showed details of the distribution. Furhter Investigation of duration in measure of minutes on a log scale as well to confirm insights.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Unusual high ages appeared in member_age column when visualizing, removed rows with ages that exceeded the oldest age in the world.
Added duration_min column for duration in minutes, as minutes measure is much easier to interpret and limits the range of values (/60). Also, added a column for the log values of duration to assist in log transformation.
Added a column for the day of the week (using start time as day of start and end rarely differs), and a column for hour of the day (with an approximation of start hour) to assist in analyzing time frequencies and patterns
